            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Saira Kapoor\u2019s story is one of rooted ambition, shaped by the immigrant experience in the East Bay. The only daughter of Punjabi parents who settled in Fremont in the late 1960s, she grew up amidst the scent of spices and the sound of relentless work. Her parents\u2019 dream was simple: for their daughter to have the opportunities they never did. Saira absorbed their work ethic but found her own calling. She watched her grandmother, a proud woman who spoke little English, struggle to navigate the American healthcare system. That experience ignited a quiet fire in her, leading her to pursue Public Health at UC Berkeley and later a Master's in Health Administration.\n\nLeaving Fremont for San Francisco after graduate school in the late 90s was a defining act of independence. She was drawn to the city's vibrant, chaotic energy and its concentration of non-profits. Saira began her career as a case manager, her empathy and administrative acumen quickly setting her apart. She rose steadily, driven by a desire to dismantle the very barriers that had frustrated her grandmother. Her career became her anchor, especially after an amicable divorce a decade ago. While her ex-husband sought a quieter life in Marin, Saira\u2019s roots in the city had grown too deep.\n\nNow, as the Director of Clinical Services for a large non-profit, Saira\u2019s life is a testament to deliberate choices. She lives in a tastefully minimalist Hayes Valley condo, just a 0.8-mile walk from her office. Her days begin with a stroll to a local cafe for an oat latte and end with yoga or a quiet dinner with her tight-knit circle of friends. Her son, now a software engineer in Austin, is her greatest pride.\n\nSaira feels an intrinsic connection to Hayes Valley, having watched it transform into a chic, artistic hub. She loves the proximity to the symphony and jazz center, but her true joy comes from the weekend farmers' market at the Civic Center. Looking ahead, Saira isn\u2019t dreaming of retirement. Instead, she aspires to use her expertise to consult for smaller community clinics or perhaps launch a culturally competent wellness program for immigrant seniors\u2014a full-circle tribute to the woman who first inspired her path."
